a 1340","1339":"1339","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hartlip, Kent, England":"Hartlip, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Osbaldeston, Lancashire, England":"Osbaldeston, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sittingbourne, Kent, England":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England"},"en":{"about 1340–about 1404":"about 1340–about 1404","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1341–1400":"1341–1400","1370–1412":"1370–1412","1370–1422":"1370–1422","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","about 1404":"about 1404","1422":"1422","1320":"1320","about 1340":"about 1340","1339":"1339","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Hartlip, Kent, England":"Hartlip, Kent, England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Osbaldeston, Lancashire, England":"Osbaldeston, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Sittingbourne, Kent, England":"Sittingbourne, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osbyrne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbon","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborne","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Oborne in Dorset. The placename derives from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’.","possibly from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]},{"name":"Orsburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbun","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Hoskin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osekin</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a pet form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Os-</i> (particularly <i>Osbert</i>, as well as <i>Osbern</i>, and <i>Osmund</i>) + the Flemish diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. All three personal names were current in medieval Cornwall or Devon; see   Osborne  ,   Osmond  , and   Opie   (a pet form of <i>Osbert</i>). Old English <i>Ōsbeorn</i>, <i>Ōsbeohrt</i>, and <i>Ōsmund</i> may also have contributed in a minor way to Middle English usage; Middle English   Oswald   is another possible source, but the name was very rare in the late 14th century. For the excrescent initial <i>H-</i>, compare   Herrick  ."]},{"name":"Osborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Orsborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborn","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name chiefly from Oborne in Dorset, or perhaps occasionally from Howbourne Farm in Hadlow Down, Sussex, Woburn in Bedfordshire, Woburn Park in Surrey, or Wooburn in Buckinghamshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, except Wooburn in Buckinghamshire, which is of uncertain etymology.","English (of Norman origin): perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]}]},{"name":"Marion","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a medieval French diminutive form of   Marie  , introduced to Britain in the Middle Ages. In some places it was taken as a pet form of   Margaret   or   Margery .  As a male name, it is an altered form of the Continental male name <i>Marian</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>Marianus</i> (from   Marius  ), but is now rarely, if ever, used. It was the birth name of the American film star  John Wayne  (  1907–79 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Marion Osbyrne was born about 1340, in Sittingbourne, Kent, England, his father, Sir John Osburn Baron of Sitting Bourne, was 21 and his mother, Lady John Osborne, was 21. He married Juliana Marion in 1370, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1404, in his hometown, at the age of 66, and was buried in Sittingbourne, Kent, England."},"et":{"about 1340–about 1404":"umbes 1340–umbes 1404","1340–1404":"1340–1404","1341–1400":"1341–1400","1370–1412":"1370–1412","1370–1422":"1370–1422","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1412":"1412","1400":"1400","about 1404":"umbes 1404","1422":"1422","1320":"1320","about 1340":"umbes 1340","1339":"1339","Hartlip Swale Cliff Kent England":"Hartlip, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sittingbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Sittingb